The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, Sept. 21: Finance minister Pranab Mukherjee today reviewed the turnaround plan of Air India, which is seeking a Rs 5,000-crore bailout package from the government. The finance minister reviewed the steps the airline was taking to cut costs and improve savings. Mukherjee was briefed on the issue by civil aviation secretary M. Madhavan Nambiar and Air India chairman Arvind Jadhav at a meeting in his North Block office, official sources said.                             
	 Coimbatore, Sept. 21: A bill to regulate private courier services will be introduced in the next session of Parliament, Union telecommunications and IT minister A. Raja said. At present, there is no provision to find legal remedy in the case of any dispute with private couriers, which have no accountability. The new bill will help protect the customer, Raja said.                             
	 New Delhi, Sept. 21: Quarterly cost audit by internal auditors of listed companies should be examined in consultation with market regulator Sebi to improve corporate governance, an expert group appointed by the corporate affairs ministry has suggested.                            
	 Mumbai, Sept. 21: Stainless steel ware manufacturer Varun Group has entered into an alliance with the Republic of Madagascar to explore uranium mines. The group has acquired 1,011 blocks and 100 more are in the process of being awarded.                             
	 New Delhi, Sept. 21: Moodys has said there is always a risk of another major event sending shock waves in financial markets, even as Asian stocks may have rebounded from the lows post the collapse of Lehman Brothers last year.                            
	 London, Sept. 21: Vodafone will revamp its brand and marketing strategy in the UK for the first time in four years to beef up its image, The Times has reported.                            
	 Mumbai, Sept. 21: The BSE, the NSE, forex, money, and futures markets remained closed today on account of Id-ul-Fitr. However, all domestic wholesale commodity markets were open for trading.                                                                                                                           
